---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';

const title = 'Fitness &amp; health app development';
const description =
  'Fitness, health and telemedicine app development for iOS and Android. Workouts, tracking, HealthKit and Google Fit integration, wearables, and secure handling of personal health data.';
---

<ServiceLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  serviceType="Fitness and health mobile app development"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
    { href: '/apps', label: 'Mobile apps' },
    { href: '/apps/fitness', label: 'Fitness &amp; health' },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Fitness and health is one of the largest app categories on both stores, and one of the
    most competitive — most people have tried two or three apps before they keep one. The apps
    that win aren't the ones with the most features; they're the ones that fit smoothly into
    a habit. We build fitness, wellness and health apps with that fit in mind, paying close
    attention to the parts that matter (onboarding, motivation, data accuracy, privacy) and
    skipping the parts that don't.
  </p>

  <h2>What we build</h2>
  <p>
    Workout apps with structured programmes (strength, hypertrophy, endurance, beginner). Class
    streaming apps (live or on-demand video, with offline downloads). Habit and tracking apps
    (steps, water, sleep, mood, supplements, custom metrics). Nutrition tracking with food
    databases and barcode scanning. Personal coach apps for trainers and their clients. Yoga,
    meditation, mindfulness and breathwork apps. Telemedicine and remote consultation apps.
    Recovery and physiotherapy apps with exercise videos and progress tracking. Run and ride
    tracking apps with maps, splits, and route saving.
  </p>

  <h2>End-to-end work</h2>

  <h3>HealthKit and Google Fit integration</h3>
  <p>
    Most fitness apps benefit from reading existing health data — steps from the user's phone,
    heart rate from a smartwatch, sleep tracked by another app, workouts from a Garmin or
    Strava. iOS does this through HealthKit; Android through Google Fit (and now Health
    Connect). We integrate both with the right permission flows and the right write-back
    behaviour (so workouts done in your app appear in Apple Fitness or Samsung Health).
  </p>

  <h3>Wearable support</h3>
  <p>
    Apple Watch companion apps with watchOS workouts and complications. Wear OS apps for
    Android. Heart-rate and sensor read from supported devices. Background sync so a workout
    started on the watch appears on the phone instantly. We design the watch interface
    separately — a watch screen with the same density as a phone screen is unusable.
  </p>

  <h3>Workout and programme structure</h3>
  <p>
    Programme builder for trainers (or for in-house content creators). Sets, reps, weights,
    tempo, rest. Supersets and circuits. Progress tracking across sessions with one-rep-max
    estimation. Form-cue videos embedded next to each exercise. Substitutions when equipment
    isn't available. We build the programme engine generic enough to support strength,
    cardio, mobility, yoga, and bodyweight without separate code paths.
  </p>

  <h3>Video content (live and on-demand)</h3>
  <p>
    For class streaming or instructor videos, we use a proper video CDN (Mux, Cloudflare
    Stream, or BunnyCDN) with adaptive bitrate so playback works on slow connections without
    buffering. Offline downloads with DRM if you sell premium content. Picture-in-picture
    support on iOS so the user can keep watching while taking notes.
  </p>

  <h3>Nutrition and food tracking</h3>
  <p>
    Food database integration (Open Food Facts, USDA, FatSecret, or Nutritionix depending on
    region and accuracy needs). Barcode scanning that works in low light. Photo recognition for
    meal logging if you want it (with realistic expectations — it's improving but still
    imperfect). Macro tracking, calorie goals, custom recipes. Water and supplement reminders.
  </p>

  <h3>Habit, tracking and motivation</h3>
  <p>
    Streaks (used carefully — they're powerful but break motivation when they snap). Weekly
    summaries. Charts that make progress visible across weeks and months, not just days.
    Reminders at the right moment in the day, learned from when the user actually opens the
    app. Achievement unlocks where appropriate; not where they feel patronising.
  </p>

  <h3>Coaching and messaging</h3>
  <p>
    For coaching apps, the trainer-client relationship is the product. Asynchronous video
    messaging (record once, play back with notes). Programme assignment per client. Progress
    review across weeks. Check-in forms. Group coaching with a feed and comments. Payment
    splits if you operate a marketplace of trainers. Stripe Connect for payouts.
  </p>

  <h3>Telemedicine and clinical features</h3>
  <p>
    Secure messaging that meets the requirements for clinical communication (in the UK, that
    typically means data residency, audit logs, and consent capture). Video consultations with
    waiting rooms (Daily.co, Twilio Video, or built on WebRTC). Prescription handling if you
    integrate with EMIS, TPP, or another clinical system. Symptom tracking. Appointment
    reminders that don't include identifying clinical detail in push notifications.
  </p>

  <h3>Privacy and data security</h3>
  <p>
    Health data has the highest privacy expectations of any app category, and the regulators
    notice. We encrypt sensitive fields at rest, transmit over TLS only, separate consent for
    different uses (the user can opt into research data sharing without opting into marketing).
    Apple's HealthKit data must stay on-device or have explicit user permission to leave.
    Google's Health Connect has similar rules. We implement these correctly so reviewers don't
    push back at submission and so users trust your app long-term.
  </p>

  <h3>Subscriptions and free trials</h3>
  <p>
    Most fitness apps run on subscription. Apple's StoreKit and Google Play Billing handle
    auto-renewal, prorated upgrades, free trials, introductory pricing, and family sharing.
    We integrate them properly with server-side receipt validation so customers can't share
    accounts trivially while still being able to use multiple devices honestly. We also add
    proper subscription management UI (cancel, pause, change plan) — Apple now requires this
    to be reachable from inside the app.
  </p>

  <h2>What it costs</h2>
  <p>
    A focused fitness app (one core feature set, subscription, basic HealthKit and wearable
    integration) starts at £25,000 for both platforms. A full coaching marketplace with video
    messaging, programme builder and trainer payouts runs £45,000 and up. A telemedicine app
    is quoted per project after discovery — clinical features and compliance work add a layer
    of complexity that depends on which jurisdictions you operate in.
  </p>

  <h2>Timeline</h2>
  <p>
    Focused fitness app MVP: twelve to sixteen weeks. Coaching marketplace: twenty to thirty
    weeks. Telemedicine: scoped per project. Throughout, you'll have a working build on
    TestFlight and Play Console internal track — we ship every fortnight.
  </p>
</ServiceLayout>
